It wouldnâ€™t be my top choice for a museum visit in Istanbul but itâ€™s a very nice collection, well laid out. There isnâ€™t a lot of information about each object. Unless you are already into Turkish and Islamic art, I may give this one a miss. Although, you can probably see everything in 30-60 minutes.

Really lovely place and glad we visited. We bought the 5 day card deal which works out cheaper. I'm surprised someone reviewed saying it's too much "Islamic art" when it's a museum for that! Haha! But never the less it is lovely and lots of old and beautiful pieces here. For religious or non religious people! VERY clean toilets and Cafe was also not expensive (20TL for a can of coke) would recommend!

Interesting to a extent. Well curated and presented pieces. I was rather hoping for more beautiful Islamic art but it has quite a heavy religious slant. If you are a devout Muslim you may find this especially interesting and possibly even revering. Anyway, itâ€™s a charming location, included in the museum card and has great views of the blue mosque.

A treasure! Beautiful building, lovely and interesting exhibits. Quiet and cool. Kahve in the lavender garden well worth 14l. One of my best Istanbul experiences, out of a lot of very good ones - possibly because after the days of bustle, noise and crowds the tranquility was particularly welcome.
Hands down the best museum I have been to when it comes to Islamic art and history! Amazing pieces are presented transporting you back to this beautiful time in history!

Highest point in Ã‡amlÄ±ca. Beautiful view over Istanbul. There is a cafe where you can eat, drink and enjoy the beautiful view over Istanbul. Only sad thing is that not only the tourist also the Turkish people leave a lot of waste on the floor. Otherwise it's an awesome place to visitÂ .

A magnificent observation deck from which you can see the whole of Istanbul. In fact, this site is located on a hill in the center of Istanbul. The views are very beautiful.

Very beautiful place! The view here is the best in Istanbul, you can see all Istanbul from here. It's one of the best places to visit is Istanbul! The Cafe's there are very cheap too and the toilets are very clean! ðŸ˜€

Beautiful little palace with great furnishings. Not a must see given Istanbul's plethora of historical sites, but very nice little gem depicting the lives of Sultans

Beautiful palace, built with money borrowed from Europe at a time Turkey's economy was collapsing.
Stunning chandeliers and fine pottery. Lovely tea garden by the duck pond. Shame that several out buildings and the tunnel were closed.
Audio commentary good system.

A beautiful Palace with an astonishing history.
I went with my family to learn some history about turkey and we loved the experience, although taking pictures wasn't permitted which was a bummer however we had a lot of fun, each family member got an ear piece that explains and gives information about every room in the Palace, its a nice and fun outing with the family and would recommend to visit during your stay in Istanbul.

Nice palace but not very old and decorated with west European stuff. It is extrange that sultans that are supposed to help their people did not used the beautiful products manufactured in Turkey. Excellent. This is a must visit, only for the magnificence. Enjoy the splurge on the building. Take a guide, you would want to know some details

A smashing trip with an important part of Ottoman history. Donâ€™t miss this spectacular fortress and experience the force and security of the Ottoman Empire. Good footwear is essential as can be a difficult climb for some, nevertheless well worth the visit.

15 TL entry fee, or ticket price.

It has some interesting sarcophagus and ceramic pieces.  The rest of the museum was closed for reparations.  I saw many better museums in different cities in Turkey, including Ephesus and Sanliurfa. I thought this one in the capital city would have more pieces and more interesting ones, but I was mistaken. In my visit, most rooms  were being refurbished. However, the available ones had interesting pieces, such as caskets beautifully sculpted which are (mostly)  part of the Roman heritage that settled in Turkey which makes this country very interesting, and full of History as a result of a clash of different cultures and this is self-evident in the pieces displayed in its different rooms.  The little garden in the cafÃ© has a set of beautiful sculptures and statues that make it magical.  I hope  they finish the restoration soon. Highly recommended!!

They have fragments of the world's first known peace treaty, the Treaty of Kadesh, between the ancient Egyptians and Hittites, which is really cool. One thing that really bummed me out though is that the "Istanbul through the ages" exhibit was closed off. That was one of the things I was looking forward to seeing the most â˜¹ï¸

reviews.text: Must do for travellers to Istanbul who enjoy Rumi' s poetry. A truly spectacular show that transcends you to a spiritual plane. The artists and backdrop is so ethereal and amazing. Very well managed. Audience is required to observe silence during the show.  Photography is not allowed.

First and foremost, this theatre is historical and pretty much unchanged architecture since the olden times. While watching the show, I was trying to imagine how it must have been in the olden times when soundboxes & dazzling ligthing were not invented. Very artistic & romantic place. I enjoyed the show thoroughly and was a spectacle to the eyes and ears. Professionals performed their best with great synchronization & rhythm. A must visit to anyone who hasn't seen it.

BEST SUFI DANCING DERVISH IN TOWN! I booked via Expedia a day before because there is an education piece, free drink and every seat is a good seat in the house. From the reviews this seems the only legit place you can book a seat, everyone is seated, and a very professional ceremony. DO NOT attend if you have no interest in mystics or spirituality - most kids and adults fell asleep. Also YOU DO NOT HAVE TO COVER UP - I wore jeans in 30 degree temp and the guy who seated us was in shorts!

The show of Rythm of the Dance is moderately good. The dances and choreography are quite basic and simple and you can see the overly rehearsed faces of the dancers that have been doing the same routine three times a week for years, specially in the women dancers.
The theater is good to be in and there are a couple of dances worth watching. I overall would recommend going here to get an overview of traditional dancing if you just have a few days in town.

I'll split my review into three parts, one for the location, one for the Sufi/Dervish show and one for the Turkish dance show.

Alright, so the location is great, the hammam is restored well and acts a good setting. The way the information about dancing is displayed within the centre is also good in my opinion. The layout for the stage also makes you feel quite close to the action.

Moving on to the Sufi/Dervish show, the show was terrible. Its boring and a waste of time and it was most likely one of the worst shows I have ever watched. I fell asleep during the show multiple times and I was sitting in the front row. My disappointment comes from the fact that I've seen multiple Sufi shows in Egypt and Turkey. There are better shows in Istanbul, don't go to the Sufi show here, it isn't worth your time or money. Thankfully, this show is held as a separate event from the other dance show held here. 

Now, to the last part. The Turkish dance show is simply great, its energetic, it fun and simply worth going to. Its great value for money, and a decent way to either or end or start the night.

reviews.text: In my opinion, this is the most impressive building in the world. Its age and size are spectacular. If you have no interest in churches or mosques, you still ought to come here. To stand where the emperors of Rome once stood is a truly humbling experience. Come at 9-10am if you can; it gets much busier shortly after that.

The famous basilica-come-mosque-come-museum. Ancient as the city itself, it is the main attraction here. 
There were some restorations around the main hall so we could not see 100% of the museum. However, the building is wonderful and you can smell the history there.
Plan 2 hours for the museum.

Any tourist will appreciate the beauty and the history of this place. A true must have. This church is so dramatic in its size that even during the busiest day you'll not feel cramped inside.  Imagine a 1000 years ago, what it was like to build such a masterpiece in a city with merely 200,000 people.

An orthodox will have a nostalgic pain deep in their heart of the times passed standing in this holy place.

One of my favourite places in the world. There is so much history and energy in the air. This was my 3rd time visiting this place, unfortunately there was some renovations going on , so the left side of the interior was covered in scaffolding. If you only have a limited time in Istanbul then this place is No.1 on the list of sites to see. Rich in history and meaning, this site will not fail to amaze you.

This is such a beautiful place, they are restoring it so one side of the big mosque is closed off with a scaffolding. I would definitely recommend anybody wish coming to Istanbul the police check this place out. There are wonderful art Works wonderful history and a lot of great things to see in this mosque. There are tour guides to walk around the mosque and you can get a earpiece to tell you every place in the mosque it is definitely worth the money if you would like to get it to a guy to tour you around the mosque. Please be careful when going to the Blue Mosque as it will be under construction for the rest of 2019.

It is a serene and refreshing place in the midst of the city, so leave time to relax and reflect. Not as busy as other places. This is not a place you will regret seeing!

reviews.text: It is a place worth visiting,whether you are orthodox christian or not. The history of this place,of people who have taken care of it,the details,and relics that are here are just stunning. You won't be sorry for visiting it.

Great place to see a different side of Istanbul and understand how multiple religions are welcomed in the country. Free to enter. The church interior is small but filled with some wonderful wall ornaments and pictures. You will only spend about 15 minutes in this place. Don't go out of your way just to see this, only go if you're in the area already (FYI - the colourful houses of balat are nonexistent and mostly dull).

A lovely oasis of calm in the middle of this chaotic city. If you are lucky you will get to meet or see the Patriarch Bartolomew. Forget the crowds at the Vatican, here you may have the whole complex to yourself.  The interior is awe inspiring from the icons to the incense and candles. Do not miss out on walking around the local neighborhood. There are jewels from all the Jewish, Christian and Islamic faiths found around every corner.

Worth a stop when you are in the area. We went in during a christening and it was interesting to witness the ceremony. Make sure to explore the area, very fun place and not as touristy as Sultanhemet or Taksim.

En. - Known as the Serpentine Column, it is a bronze column located inside the Hippodrome of Constantinople, modern Istanbul, Turkey. It is part of an ancient Greek sacrificial tripod, originally in Delphi and relocated to Constantinople by Constantine the Great in AD 324. It was built to commemorate the Greeks who fought and defeated the Persian Empire at the Battle of Plataea in 479 BC. The serpent heads remained intact until the end of the 17th century, its provenance is almost 2,500 years old. Together with its original golden tripod and cauldron (both long missing), it constituted a trophy, or offering reminding of a military victory, dedicated to Apollo at Delphi. This offering was made in 478 BC, several months after the defeat of the Persian army in the Battle of Plataea in 479 BC by those Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars.

Among the several historical monuments of the Sultanahmet square we came across the so-called serpent column. It is set, with other monuments up in the middle of the Hippodrome also dubbed the spina. The Serpent Column, known in the old days as the Tripod of Plataea, celebrated the victory of the Greeks over the Persians during the Persian Wars in the 5th century BC. It was moved from the Temple of Apollo at Delphi, and set in middle of the Hippodrome. The top was adorned with a golden bowl supported by three serpent heads. We donâ€™t see the heads anymore; however some parts of the heads were recovered and are displayed at the Istanbul Archaeology Museum. In fact, they report that the serpent heads and top third of the column were destroyed in 1700. Nonetheless, it is a charming place to visit while in Istanbul. AnadoluhisarÄ±Â (English:Â Anatolian Castle), known historically asÂ GÃ¼zelce HisarÂ ("the Beauteous Castle]) is a medievalÂ fortresslocated inÂ Istanbul,Â TurkeyÂ on theÂ Anatolian(Asian) side of theÂ Bosporus. The complex is the oldest surviving Turkish architectural structure built in Istanbul, and further gives its name to the neighborhood around it in the city'sÂ BeykozÂ district.
AnadoluhisarÄ± was built between 1393 and 1394 on the commission of theÂ OttomanSultanÂ Bayezid I, as part of his preparations for a siege on the then-ByzantineÂ city ofÂ Constantinople, the naval blockade of which took place in 1395 under Bayezid's orders.

Constructed on an area of 7,000 square metres (1.7 acres), the fortress is situated at the narrowmost point of theÂ Bosporus, where the strait is a mere 660 meters (2,170Â ft) wide. The site is bound by GÃ¶ksu (Ancient Greek:Â AretÃ²s) creek to the south, and was previously home to the ruins of aÂ RomanÂ temple dedicated toÂ Uranus.[2]Â Erected primarily as a watch fort, the citadel has a 25 meters (82Â ft) tall, quadratic main tower within the walls of an irregular pentagon, with five watchtowers at the corners.

After Bayezid's campaign was first interrupted by theÂ Crusade of Nicopolis, and then theÂ Battle of Ankara, an 11-yearÂ period of turmoiltook hold of the Ottomans, which ended with the ascent ofÂ Mehmed IÂ to the throne. His grandson, SultanÂ Mehmed IIÂ reinforced the fortress with a two-meter-thick wall and three additional watchtowers, and added further extensions, including a warehouse and living quarters. As part of his plans to launch a renewed military campaign to conquer Constantinople, Mehmed II further built a sister structure to AnadoluhisarÄ± across the Bosphorus calledÂ RumelihisarÄ±, and the two fortresses worked in tandem in 1453 to throttle all maritime traffic along the Bosphorus, thus helping the Ottomans achieve their goal of making the city ofÂ ConstantinopleÂ (later renamedÂ Istanbul) their new imperial capital.

After theÂ Ottoman conquest of the city, AnadoluhisarÄ± served as a customs house and military prison, and after several centuries, fell into disrepair.

After theÂ fall of the OttomansÂ and the 1923 establishment of theÂ Republic of Turkey, the newly-createdÂ Turkish Ministry of Culturetended to and ultimately restored the site in 1991 - 1993. Today, AnadoluhisarÄ± lends aÂ picturesqueÂ appearance to its corner of the Bosphorus alongside the timberÂ yalÄ±Â homes that define the neighborhood, and functions as a historical site, although it is not open to the public.

reviews.text:
Definately one of the Istanbul highlights. Exceptionally well maintained (doesn't look it's 450 years!) And set in lovely gardens.

Easy to access with great views of the water as well.

Free to enter.

Absolutely incredible structure that left me in awe. It was certainly less crowded than the more popular Hagia Sofia and blue mosque, but I went later in the day around 1830. Visitors were allowed and clothing was offered at the door. If you're traveling to Istanbul, don't miss this beauty!

Suleymaniye Mosque is one of the oldest mosques in Istanbul. It is located on top of a hill with a beautiful view over the city and the Bosphorus. The construction and architecture of the mosque are fascinating. So much attention to details in every piece of the building. Open for free for the public. Modest dress code is recommended. Definitely worth visiting.

Another one of the grandest structures in Istanbul with so much of history attached to it. The best way to go there is to walk up. There are specific entrances for visitors and at the time of prayers the mosque is closed for visitors. 
You need to cover your head and your legs while going in.

A great experience as there was not much of a crowd as compared to the Blue Mosque. Also, volunteers present helped answer some of the questions which I have about the mosque and its unique at architectural style distinct from the mosques often seen in Southeast Asia.

A great place to visit, rich in history of Islam and also includes souvenirs of most of the prophets of Islam and Christianity. Also it is well maintained and coordinated. To avoid the rush the best time to visit is in March April

Topkapi Palace is marvelous. It is a must-see during the visit to Istanbul.
Plan to have more than 5 hours inside as they close by 8pm. We started at 4 and felt as if we just scratched the surface by 7:45!
Start from the right and make your way through the kitchen ( we spent 90 minutes there alone!) And go deeper until you see everything.
I highly recommend this visit. My family and I enjoyed our time. There is a mosque to pray if you want.

Located just around the corner to Aya Sophia. Has good access for wheelchair users. It's best to go in the morning as the ticket line can go all the way to the entrance. So many historical and beautiful things to see. Will take a good 4-5 hours to be able to see everything. There are a few areas where photography is not allowed. Security guards are located in each area. Overall worth the money. Some sections are barred off due to refurbishment. However the main areas such as the Prophet SAW artifacts are open to see.

It was very beautiful and you will stay there at least for 3-4 hours. So many different things to visit. Itâ€™s better to come early because many people visit that place and you will have long queue. A place to visit in Istanbul.

One of the best places that I have ever visited. The place houses so many things of historical importance and gives a fair idea of the grandeur of Ottoman Empire. And the Holy Relics of Islam that are here have no parallels in the world. For a Muslim things get really overwhelming in the chamber of Holy Relics

In my opinion this place values history, culture and effectively mixes with the modern world

reviews.text: Magnificent mosque!! This mosque is a must-see for any tourist. One of the finest architectural mosque buildings in the world. Unfortunately it was under heavy construction and renovation that blocked a lot of the beautiful walls. Itâ€™s also called the Blue Mosque due to the blue color of the countless ceramic tiles that make the interior really gorgeous. Women have to cover their head and hands, if you didnâ€™t bring a cover with you thereâ€™s a cabin at the entrance of the mosque that provides head covers and skirts free of charge! Shoes have to be taken off too, plastic bags are also provided for free so you can carry your shoes with you. Itâ€™s very charming... words canâ€™t describe it!

Historical architecture, beautiful surrounding. Free to access the building no entry fee. 

There is a dress code in place, no revealing clothes allowed if you're planning to enter the mosque, However, there is a booth inside the compound that gives out costumes to cover yourself which is also free.

It's always full of tourists taking pictures and picnicking on the mosque grounds, very beautiful at nights too.

 I should say it's very safe always police at presence, we never came across any problems while we were there.

It's one of those must see places.

This was a very pleasant experience, there is some renovation taking place that obscured your view of the amazing ceiling once inside.

It was disappointing seeing other tourist not being respectful of the nature of the building (uncovering hair once inside, a few not covering their legs and one trying to put plastic bags on her feet). 

It was good that head scarfs and leggings were provided.

The building itself is very impressive but so are the grounds.

Do you research, be respectful this is a place of worship after all.

It was great to visit the Sultan Ahmed mosque and feel the magnificence when seeing this great Islamic site. The mosque is large enough to host thousands of worshipers and part of it for tourists to enjoy the place. There are rules tourists have to follow when visiting the mosque, like taking off shoes (you will be having a plastic bag to put shoes in while you are inside the mosque),  also not shorts allowed for men, and women should dress decently (the will be given a scarf to cover their hair or shoulders). The mosque is surrounded by other monuments, shops and restaurants.

Beautiful mosque with impressive architecture, it's currently undergoing renovation and therefore has many parts of the building covered up. Tourists who are planning to visit will have to observe the rules of visiting a mosque, long pants for men and headscarf for ladies, you'll be given a plastic bag to remove and carry your shoes. Headscarves are available for ladies, but it's best to bring your own. Entry is free but you can make a donation to the mosque at the exit.

reviews.text: The museum is so big and contains so many exhibits it took us several hours to move around and we it wasn't enough to see all items. It's by far the most wonderful museum we visited in Istanbul. It contains all one can imagine of equipment and transport machines as well as models of Turkish houses over history. There's also a part of scientific experiments for children to use their heads and hands. You can also enjoy a train ride, a vessel or a submarine tour on weekends (that's Saturdays and Sundays), but there's an age limit for submarine tour ( 7 as I remember). the museums located on both sides of the main street, so don't miss any of part of it.

This is a brilliant museum with lots of exhibits including cars, trains, aeroplanes and boats. It is great for the children as there are vehicles that can be viewed as well as a mathematical problems room with lots of puzzles to solve. We have visited a few times and still haven't seen all of it.

Amazing, a must see place in Ä°stanbul. So huge you need hours but worth it. Tickets are cheap, very clean toilets every where if you have kids. Restorant and break area among old cars and aircrafts. Must see the submarine, but it comes under a different ticket.
You may also donate to assist preserve the museum if you want.
Very high quality museum. Many pieces to see and to do. A clear recommendation. There is discount for the museum card. Also inform yourself about the small guided tours you may book.

The place is perfect to go with family and friends. It has cars. Boats. Train and planes. And kids games too. The view was amazing and the atmosphere is warm.. Fees for students is 7 lira.. Very cheap

Very big park i couldb't finish it . We were there during the spring vacation and the park was filled with the tulip flowers because it was the tulip festival in Istanbul. I brought my mother with me she enjoyed a lot but the problem was that my mom can't walk or stand for a long time so i had to bring her a wheelchair which was very difficult to push uphill. Close to the entrance of the park u can find very nice cafes

It is incredible park, families and kids can spend whole day enjoying their moment, a lot of activities can be done. You can kook and do BBq, the most beautiful is the sea view from the park, you can see Istanbul bridge which will take you to feel peace of mind. I am strongly recommended this place, don't miss the chance to go over there while visiting Istanbul

Nice and big park open for the public all day long. Worth visiting during spring because it usually gets filled with tulips. The downside is that the park is not clean. Unfortunately, some people don't clean after themselves. I hope there would be some kind of penalty for littering.

Perfect place for relaxation. You can eat at the Yellow Mansion which is on the opposite side of the Pink Mansion. There are many places where you can sit and take photos with friends and family. Entrance fee if you want to enter the park in car is 10 TL. Overall it is the place to spend time with your family.

This park was in my trip design created by Tripster. I have visited here during Tulip season in Istanbul and got fascinated by the beauty of various tulips. Learned the best spots from my travel designer and took great photos. Nice and big park open for the public all day long. Worth visiting during spring because it usually gets filled with tulips.

reviews.text: What a nice area. Small part of Western Europe in the city. Drastically different to most of tourist placed.
I like the atmosphere of the place. It is always festive and joyful. There is a cute little market place with souvenirs and Pier Loti cafe with fantastic views on the HaliÃ§ nearby.
Love this place and Shrine or Hazrat Ayub Ansari. Manage and good environment. Prophet Muhammad's beard hair is also preserve there. Love to feed pigeons out side of mosque
Excellent and important place to visit. The cafe at the top of the hill is excellent. You can also talked the cable car to the top with your Istanbul kart.

Must visit whilst in Istanbul. The great Companion and Relative of the Prophet Muhammad ï·º.full of Barakah, peace and tranquility. The surrounding shops, community, buzz and people are amazing. 
Visiting the tomb of Abu Ayub Sultan is an outstanding experience. He was the friend of prophet Mohammad peace be upon him !

Fantastic attraction that is well worth the visit. This spacious Roman built cistern shows off impressive Roman engineering. There are two large cistern rooms that are accessible through a tastefully lit walk way. The cistern is also lit along each column without the lighting being too strong so you get a great feel for the space.

At the end of the second room, there is a massive Medusa embellished column, that's worth going all the way for. Information boards tell you the history and point out details along the way.

It's a beautiful space.

Note that entry is not covered by the museum card, but there is a flat entry charge.

One of the most magical places I have ever seen. Visited it several times and every time it took my breath away. By design a pure engineering structure (water cistern for the Eastern Roman capital of Constantinople) has an immense beauty intensified by the perfectly managed lighting and mirroring of the light on the surface of the water. Worth every lira of the admission costs. Try to keep quiet in order not to spoil the experience for others.

A great and an unusual attraction to visit while in Istanbul. It is fascinating to see such constructions were built for hundreds of years ago. Perfect for a hot summer day. It is not always filled with water but still worth visiting even if it was empty. Entrance costs 10TL per person. Recommended.
Was very cool, nice and different. A good place to escape the heat. The Medusa heads are cool. It was 20 lira to get in so wasn't too expensive. You don't need long in there.

While often overcrowded and congested the Basilica Cistern offers a beautiful insight into some lost history in the heard of Istanbul. Visible damage caused by building on-top of the lost cistern can be seen in cracks in the columns and pathced holes in the ceiling of the area. An ultimately beautiful sight to take in and a perfect place to come during the hotter parts of the day. Take your time and explore each column individually, read the signs and take it all in.

reviews.text: Grand Bazaar is made up of several different types of markets. You'll have clothing, spices, housewares and jewellery to name a few. Each market has their own little section in the bazaar. Some of it is housed indoors like a small mall while others will be outside. If you're one for negotiating don't hesitate as it's common. They also have food throughout the bazaar mainly around the outskirts of the market.

A superb market area with history and character. However, beware shop sellers are like vultures with a sweet face and smile. Really , they overcharge as prices are highly inflated compared to other sites and places. All items including, footwear, leather goods, bags and Jewellery, watches, etc can be found elsewhere within Istanbul, so haggle down to less than half the asking price or you will be definitely paying above the odds! But, all in all, you will need to allow a day or two or even more to properly explore shop and enjoy the experience. Be sure to explore the shopping around the edges of the market as they provide a better price overall. Just relax and enjoy the Grand Bazar ottoman experience.

It was super crowded and air conditioned in only some places. The prices were not as low as I had hoped even when calculating/converting the Turkish Lira to US dollar. I did make some purchases, e.g. bought a 100% cotton white bathrobe for 70 TL, which is about $12. It wasn't your typical terry sort of material, it was the thin, waffle-stitched sort - less bulky and more absorbent. That was a great deal! I bought 8 pot/pan decorated coasters as souvenirs - look around until you find the merchants that sell them for 10 TL - there are some selling them for 15 and 20 TL.

As it name suggests ,it is a great experience,with the variety of things sold there,it surely a tourist delight. The coated nuts and ceramic plates etc were amazing. You can wander about and pick up anything to.take back home. I could pick up something for all my loved ones back home. The atmosphere was electrifying. Each seller trying his best to sell his wares. Of course one had to bargain a lot.

Great experience! A must visit if you are in Istanbul. We went there three times during our visit to Istanbul and had a splendid day each time! Make sure to bargain before you make a deal, always start at a third of the asking price! They have a wide variety of items. You can pretty much buy anything here, from jewellery to souvenirs to leather stuff to delicious food.
